      <notesstmt>
        <note>Fol. 1r, under the heading &#1508;&#1494;&#1502;&#1493;&#1503;, is Abraham ben Samuel Abulafia's kabbalic poem for Shavuot&#1488;&#1513;&#1514;&#1506;&#1513;&#1506; &#1489;&#1502;&#1513;(&#1488;)&#1500; &#1511;&#1491;&#1502;&#1493;&#1503;, which ends in praise for Maimonides. See Steinschneider, Kov&#803;ets &#697;al yad, sidrah 1, kerehh 1 (1885), p. 4, 15. Followed by Hebrew instructions for preparing a prescription for sorts of leprosy. Together they are 17 lines, the remainder of the page is empty; Fol. 1v contains various remedies in Judeo-Arabic; Fol. 2v contains a potion in Hebrew for a thin man or woman who wishes to be fat; remainder of the page is empty.</note>
        <note>Condition: complete, fading ; fol. 2r is empty.</note>
      </notesstmt>
